Late momentum for Biden. Polls showing a move his direction even before the South Carolina results on Saturday. https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/tx/texas_democratic_primary-6875.html FiveThirtyEight rating Biden as a slight favorite. https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/super-tuesday-preview-sanders-and-biden-are-duking-it-out-in-texas/
Recent endorsements nudging Biden up. Very fluid.

The polls indicate that Bernie has been able to consolidate his support in Texas to hover around a crucial winning amount of 30%. Moreover, the polls show no drop in support for Bernie or increase for Biden since South Carolina, indicating that Biden's performance hasn't had much of an effect in Texas. Furthermore, Bernie remain extremely popular among Hispanic voters, which propelled him to huge win in Nevada and will more than likely propel him forward in Texas as well.

I'm going against majority opinion here but I think Biden has a much better chance than the crowd suggest. The latest polls put him neck and neck with Sanders and he seems to be starting to regain the popularity he had in this state before Iowa. With it looking like Biden will win convincingly in South Carolina I think his surge here is set to continue.

You know what they say about Texas, “Texas is Texas…” Though outsiders would label Texas as part of “The South,” Texas is its own special entity with very specific priorities that does not like the government playing too much in the life of a typical Texan. This is why I do not think Sanders will do well in Texas because he is “too far to the left” for most in the state. I think many in Texas relate more to Biden and Buttigieg than any of the other candidates.

The focus here will be on non-New York centrists who are seen as being able to beat Trump. Klobuchar may do well here, with Biden a familiar and safe face. Buttigieg will have issues with non-white voters, and Sanders and Warren will be a distinct minority in TX.
